<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="contextual-inquiry">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Field research in user's work environment with observation, questioning, and shared interpretation.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>contextual</tag>
      <tag>inquiry</tag>
      <tag>field-research</tag>
      <tag>observation</tag>
      <tag>qualitative</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>research</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Contextual Inquiry</title>
    <summary>Contextual inquiry is a semi-structured field research method conducted in the user's actual work environment while tasks unfold. The researcher observes, asks questions, and shares interpretations for immediate correction using the master-apprentice model: user is the expert, researcher is the learner.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Lab interviews capture what people think they do; contextual inquiry captures what they actually do. Workarounds, tacit knowledge, physical artifacts, and environmental constraints only surface in context. The master-apprentice framing and shared-interpretation principle produce richer, more accurate data than recall-based methods while reducing observer-effect distortion.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Discovery research where workflows, tools, and physical environment matter (clinical, factory, financial back-office, field ops).</item>
        <item>Mapping current-state tasks before redesign — capturing workarounds, shadow IT, and tacit knowledge.</item>
        <item>Validating that a new product fits real work, not idealized work, before spec freeze.</item>
        <item>Investigating incidents where reported procedure diverges from actual practice.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quick usability feedback on a finished design — usability testing is faster and cheaper.</item>
        <item>Pure attitudinal or preference questions — surveys are sufficient.</item>
        <item>High-secrecy environments (defense, M&amp;A) where observation is restricted — fall back to artifact analysis.</item>
        <item>Remote-only access where physical artifacts cannot be observed — use diary studies instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="four-principles">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Conduct the session in the user's actual work environment, not a lab or meeting room.</statement>
        <rationale>Context principle: removing the user from their environment removes the environmental triggers, physical artifacts, and interruptions that shape real behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat the user as the expert and the researcher as the apprentice (learner). Use the opening script to establish this frame before observation begins.</statement>
        <rationale>Partnership principle: the master-apprentice model reduces observer-effect distortion. Users perform naturally when they are the acknowledged authority.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Share interpretations aloud during the session and invite corrections: "So it seems like... Did I understand correctly?"</statement>
        <rationale>Interpretation principle: researchers form wrong mental models continuously. Surfacing and correcting them in-session prevents compounded misinterpretations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enter each session with clear research questions. The observation guide must specify which aspects of work to observe and what questions to answer.</statement>
        <rationale>Focus principle: without a defined lens, sessions produce unfocused notes. Clear focus enables selective attention without missing key phenomena.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="what-to-capture">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Record these seven data types for every session: actions taken, tools used, artifacts created or used, physical environment description, interruptions, workarounds, and frustrations expressed verbally.</statement>
        <rationale>Comprehensive capture prevents the most common loss: workarounds and physical artifacts that hold the real workflow are easy to overlook.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Mark inferences as inferences in notes from the very first session. Write observed vs inferred in separate fields; retroactive separation after analysis is impossible.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixing observed and inferred data produces false confidence in downstream analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="process-steps">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define focus areas, recruit 4-8 participants for one focus area, obtain organizational permission, prepare recording equipment, and create an observation guide before the first session.</statement>
        <rationale>4-8 sessions is the sweet spot for one focus area — enough to find patterns across participants without spending more sessions than new insights warrant.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a 1-hour pilot before the real round to fix observation-guide weaknesses. The second guide is always better.</statement>
        <rationale>Guides written before observation contain leading questions and missing focus areas that only become visible when used in the field.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Watch silently first, then ask about specific observed actions: "Why did you do that?" Never suggest improvements or express surprise at workarounds during the session.</statement>
        <rationale>Premature suggestions and expressed surprise alter behavior immediately.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Capture artifacts physically (photos with consent). Workflows rarely live entirely on screens; paper notes, whiteboard scribbles, and handwritten forms are primary data.</statement>
        <rationale>Remote CI variants cannot capture physical artifacts, which is a significant data loss.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Debrief within 30 minutes of each session, while peripheral memory is intact. Audio recording does not replace immediate debrief.</statement>
        <rationale>Peripheral memory (environmental details, emotional tone, gestural context) decays within hours.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>After all sessions: identify patterns using affinity diagrams, sequence models, and cultural models.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-session insights are anecdotes. Cross-session analysis transforms observations into findings.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="remote-adaptations">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>When in-person access is not possible, use screen share plus webcam to capture some environmental context; supplement with self-documentation or diary study. Always acknowledge that remote CI loses physical artifacts and reduces environmental signal.</statement>
        <rationale>Remote CI captures ~60-70% of the signal of in-person CI. The loss is concentrated in physical artifacts, peripheral activities, and environmental triggers.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>LLM agents accelerate the labor-heavy back half (transcription, tagging, affinity clustering, model drafting), but the observation itself is human. Pipeline: (1) human researcher records in-environment session with consent + minimal cues, (2) transcript-cleaner agent normalizes ASR output and timestamps, (3) observation-tagger extracts actions/artifacts/breakdowns into structured rows, (4) affinity-clusterer proposes clusters with evidence, (5) model-drafter outputs sequence/flow/cultural model skeletons for human review. Always re-share interpretations with participants — agents cannot self-validate.</p>
      <note>Recommended subagents: transcript-cleaner (haiku; fixes ASR errors, aligns speakers, redacts PII); observation-tagger (sonnet; extracts {time, actor, action, artifact, tool, breakdown, quote} rows); affinity-clusterer (sonnet; clusters tagged rows across sessions, names clusters, surfaces outliers); workflow-modeler (sonnet; drafts sequence and flow models for designer review); interview-coach (sonnet; pre-session reviewer that critiques the observation guide for leading/loaded questions).</note>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Time-boxed sessions (1-2 h) miss low-frequency tasks (monthly close, quarterly audits) and emergencies. Sample for role, shift, seniority, and edge-case variation — not statistical validity.</statement>
        <rationale>Contextual inquiry is not a representative sample; it is a qualitative deep dive. Selecting for variation ensures the findings cover the range of work patterns, not just the most common ones.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Observer effect is real; participants perform their work for the researcher, missing the messy reality. Master-apprentice framing assumes a single expert; team-based work needs a different choreography.</statement>
        <rationale>Acknowledging observer effect and adapting method for team settings are part of rigorous CI practice. Design-by-observation without acknowledging these limits produces false confidence.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a 1-hour pilot before the real round to fix observation-guide weaknesses; the second guide is always better.</statement>
        <rationale>Guides written before observation contain leading questions and missing focus areas that only become visible when used in the field.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Capture artifacts physically (photos with consent) — workflows rarely live entirely on screens.</statement>
        <rationale>Paper notes, whiteboard scribbles, and handwritten forms are primary data that screen-only capture misses.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Mark inferences as inferences in notes from the very first session; retroactive separation of observed vs inferred is impossible.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixing observed and inferred data produces false confidence. Downstream agents and designers treat both as equally grounded unless the distinction is explicit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Debrief within 30 minutes of the session, while peripheral memory is intact. Audio recording does not replace this.</statement>
        <rationale>Peripheral memory (environmental details, emotional tone, gestural context) decays within hours. Recordings capture only what the microphone picked up.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sample for variation, not statistical validity: include shifts, regions, seniority, edge-case roles. 4-8 sessions is the sweet spot for one focus area.</statement>
        <rationale>Contextual inquiry finds patterns across variation. Selecting only typical users produces findings that miss the edge cases that break system assumptions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Share interim findings with participants ("member checking") to catch misinterpretations before downstream design work commits to them.</statement>
        <rationale>Researchers form incorrect interpretations even with shared-interpretation protocol. Participant validation is the final check before findings become design inputs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat workarounds as system-design signals, not user errors. The fact that someone keeps paper notes is the finding.</statement>
        <rationale>Workarounds reveal where the designed system diverges from how work actually happens. Treating them as errors misses the most valuable design signals.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-rules">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs paraphrase quotes silently when summarizing transcripts.</description>
        <reason>Lock the tagging agent to verbatim mode: any string in the output not present verbatim in the source transcript is a hallucination. Reject paraphrases for the quote field.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Privacy: observation sessions capture bystanders, screen contents, and dictation not belonging to the participant.</description>
        <reason>Redact non-participant PII using a tool like presidio before any LLM ingestion. Remote CI screen recordings often include private windows — pre-trim before sharing with any third-party tool.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent ranks participant competence, labeling "wrong" workflows as user error.</description>
        <reason>The finding is always that the system does not fit real work. An agent that judges the workflow as incorrect misses the most valuable signal: workarounds reveal system design failures.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Never substitute an LLM-simulated user for a real participant ("synthetic CI").</description>
        <reason>LLMs have no sensory access to real workplaces. Any "observation" they produce is extrapolation from training data, not from the actual environment being studied.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/observation-guide.md" purpose="Pre-session guide: focus areas, opening script, observation checklist, notes table."/>
      <template path="templates/session-notes.md" purpose="Structured post-session notes: environment, workflow sequences, workarounds, insights."/>
      <template path="templates/ci-row-schema.py" purpose="Dataclass for a single tagged observation row used in cross-session analysis."/>
    </templates>
    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/observation_tagger_prompt.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for extracting structured observation rows from transcripts."/>
    </scripts>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/contextual-inquiry/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
